  {q:"What is sector rotation?",a:"Sector rotation is an investment strategy that moves money between stock market sectors based on the current phase of the economic cycle. Different sectors outperform at different stages — technology and consumer discretionary tend to lead during early recovery, while utilities and consumer staples outperform during recessions. Investors use sector rotation to position portfolios ahead of economic shifts, overweighting sectors expected to benefit from the next phase."},
  {q:"What are the 11 GICS sectors?",a:"The Global Industry Classification Standard (GICS) divides the stock market into 11 sectors: Information Technology (XLK), Health Care (XLV), Financials (XLF), Consumer Discretionary (XLY), Consumer Staples (XLP), Energy (XLE), Utilities (XLU), Industrials (XLI), Materials (XLB), Real Estate (XLRE), and Communication Services (XLC). Each has a corresponding SPDR Select Sector ETF that tracks S&P 500 companies in that sector."},
  {q:"Which sectors perform best in a recession?",a:"Defensive sectors historically outperform during recessions: Consumer Staples (XLP), Utilities (XLU), and Health Care (XLV). These sectors provide essential goods and services — food, electricity, and medical care — that consumers need regardless of economic conditions. Utility stocks benefit from regulated revenue streams and high dividend yields that attract safety-seeking investors."},
  {q:"Which sectors perform best during economic recovery?",a:"Cyclical sectors lead during recoveries: Consumer Discretionary (XLY), Financials (XLF), Industrials (XLI), and Technology (XLK). As the economy rebounds, consumers increase discretionary spending, banks benefit from rising loan demand, and industrial companies see growing orders. Real Estate (XLRE) also benefits from low interest rates that typically accompany early recovery."},
  {q:"How do I track sector rotation?",a:"Track sector rotation by monitoring relative performance across multiple timeframes. Rising sectors on shorter timeframes that lag on longer ones may signal a new rotation. Key indicators include: sector ETF relative strength vs. SPY, yield curve shape, ISM Manufacturing PMI, and consumer confidence. Our tracker above provides performance comparison across five timeframes."},
  {q:"What are sector ETFs and how do they work?",a:"Sector ETFs hold stocks from a single market sector. The SPDR Select Sector ETFs divide the S&P 500 into 11 sector funds. Each ETF holds only companies classified in that GICS sector, weighted by market cap. They trade like stocks with real-time pricing, charge 0.09% expense ratios, and allow investors to overweight or underweight specific sectors without picking individual stocks."},
  {q:"What is the best sector to invest in right now?",a:"The best sector depends on the economic cycle phase and your investment horizon. As of Q1 2026, Technology (XLK) and Communication Services (XLC) show strong momentum driven by AI spending. However, sector leadership rotates — chasing recent performance often means buying near the top. Check the performance table above for current rankings across multiple timeframes."},
  {q:"How does the economic cycle affect sector performance?",a:"The economic cycle has four phases: (1) Early Recovery — Financials, Consumer Discretionary, Real Estate, and Technology lead. (2) Expansion — Technology, Industrials, and Materials outperform. (3) Slowdown — Energy, Health Care, and Consumer Staples gain. (4) Recession — Utilities, Consumer Staples, and Health Care provide safety. Understanding these patterns helps investors position ahead of macro turning points."}
];

